d.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Miss ferch Ifor was born about 1195, in Breconshire, Wales as the daughter of Ifor ap Rhiwallon."},"et":{"ABT    1195–":"umbes 1195–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"umbes 1230","1200":"1200","ABT    1195":"umbes 1195","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"fi":{"ABT    1195–":"noin 1195–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1202":"1202","ABT    1230